Comparison of median frequency of a whole train

Hypothesis

H_0: There is no difference in the distribution of the median frequency (whole train) between the german and danish harbour porpoise clicks

Exploratory Analysis

summary(Ref_DE$medianKHz)
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##    28.0   120.0   123.0   123.2   126.0   144.0
summary(Ref_DK$medianKHz)
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##      84     122     125     125     128     146

Visualization/Plots:

Check Requirements for tests

Normality of Distribution

  • size of Dataframe too large for Shapiro-Wilk Test

  • using Q-Q-Plots to get a visual idea and Kolmogorov-Smirnov Test as an alternative

Median Frequency DE:

## 
##  Asymptotic one-sample Kolmogorov-Smirnov test
## 
## data:  Ref_DE$medianKHz
## D = 0.09672, p-value < 2.2e-16
## alternative hypothesis: two-sided

Median Frequency DK:

## 
##  Asymptotic one-sample Kolmogorov-Smirnov test
## 
## data:  Ref_DK$medianKHz
## D = 0.054253, p-value < 2.2e-16
## alternative hypothesis: two-sided

No noticeable normal distribution in Q-Q-Plot which is underlined by the result of the Kolmogorov-Smirnov-Test.
The small p-value (<2.2e-16) suggest that the distribution significantly differs from normal distribution.

Also checking for homogeneity of variances (Levenes Test):

## Levene's Test for Homogeneity of Variance (center = median)
##           Df F value   Pr(>F)   
## group      1  7.9812 0.004727 **
##       298231                    
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1

p-value (0.004727) < 0.05
> statistically significant difference in variances between the groups
Therefore the null hypothesis of homogeneity of variances is rejected.

Statistical Test (Wilcoxon)

## 
##  Wilcoxon rank sum test with continuity correction
## 
## data:  Ref_DE$medianKHz and Ref_DK$medianKHz
## W = 8.457e+09, p-value < 2.2e-16
## alternative hypothesis: true location shift is not equal to 0

p (<2.2e-16) < 0.05
> there is a significant difference between the datasets for the criterion median frequency
